# Event-Driven Patterns

## Event Naming Convention

Use `domain.action` format:

```typescript
// Good
this.eventEmitter.emit("game.handStarted", { gameId, handNumber });
this.eventEmitter.emit("tournament.botRegistered", { tournamentId, botId });
this.eventEmitter.emit("bot.healthCheckFailed", { botId, reason });

// Bad - inconsistent naming
this.eventEmitter.emit("startHand", data);
this.eventEmitter.emit("TOURNAMENT_PLAYER_JOIN", data);
```

## Emitting Events

```typescript
import { EventEmitter2 } from "@nestjs/event-emitter";

@Injectable()
export class MyService {
  constructor(private readonly eventEmitter: EventEmitter2) {}

  async doSomething(): Promise<void> {
    // Business logic first
    await this.repository.save(entity);
    
    // Emit event after successful operation
    this.eventEmitter.emit("domain.actionCompleted", {
      entityId: entity.id,
      timestamp: new Date(),
    });
  }
}
```

## Listening to Events

```typescript
import { OnEvent } from "@nestjs/event-emitter";

@Injectable()
export class MetricsCollectorService {
  @OnEvent("game.handStarted")
  handleHandStarted(event: { gameId: string; handNumber: number }): void {
    this.metricsService.incrementHandsDealt();
  }
}
```

## When to Use Events vs Direct Calls

**Use events for:**
- Decoupled side effects (metrics, logging, notifications)
- Multiple listeners for one action
- Cross-module communication without tight coupling

**Use direct calls for:**
- Core business logic that must succeed
- When you need the return value
- Synchronous validation
